\par }{\i\fs20\cf0 Wish }{\fs20\cf0 is the mightiest spell a wizard or sorcerer can cast. By simply speaking aloud, you can alter reality to better suit you.
\par Even }{\i\fs20\cf0 wish}{\fs20\cf0 , however, has its limits.
\par A }{\i\fs20\cf0 wish }{\fs20\cf0 can produce any one of the following effects.
\par }{\cf0 \bullet  }{\fs20\cf0 Duplicate any wizard or sorcerer spell of 8th level or lower, provided the spell is not of a school prohibited to you.
\par }{\cf0 \bullet  }{\fs20\cf0 Duplicate any other spell of 6th level or lower, provided the spell is not of a school prohibited to you.
\par }{\cf0 \bullet  }{\fs20\cf0 Duplicate any wizard or sorcerer spell of 7th level or lower even if it\rquote s of a prohibited school.
\par }{\cf0 \bullet  }{\fs20\cf0 Duplicate any other spell of 5th level or lower even if it\rquote s of a prohibited school. 
\par }{\cf0 \bullet  }{\fs20\cf0 Undo the harmful effects of many other spells, such as }{\i\fs20\cf0 geas/quest }{\fs20\cf0 or }{\i\fs20\cf0 insanity}{\fs20\cf0 .
\par }{\cf0 \bullet  }{\fs20\cf0 Create a nonmagical item of up to 25,000 gp in value.
\par }{\cf0 \bullet  }{\fs20\cf0 Create a magic item, or add to the powers of an existing magic item.
\par }{\cf0 \bullet  }{\fs20\cf0 Grant a creature a +1 inherent bonus to an ability score. Two to five }{\i\fs20\cf0 wish }{\fs20\cf0 
spells cast in immediate succession can grant a creature a +2 to +5 inherent bonus to an ability score (two wishes for a +2 inherent bonus, three for a +3 inherent bonus, and so on). Inherent bonuses are instantaneous, so they cannot be dispelled. }{
\i\fs20\cf0 Note: }{\fs20\cf0 An inherent bonus may not exceed +5 for a single ability score, and inherent bonuses to a particular ability score do not stack, so only the best one applies.
\par }{\cf0 \bullet  }{\fs20\cf0 Remove injuries and afflictions. A single }{\i\fs20\cf0 wish }{\fs20\cf0 can aid one creature per caster level, and all subjects are cured of the same kind of affli
ction. For example, you could heal all the damage you and your companions have taken, or remove all poison effects from everyone in the party, but not do both with the same }{\i\fs20\cf0 wish}{\fs20\cf0 . A }{\i\fs20\cf0 wish }{\fs20\cf0 
can never restore the experience point loss from casting a spell or the level or Constitution loss from being raised from the dead.
\par }{\cf0 \bullet  }{\fs20\cf0 Revive the dead. A }{\i\fs20\cf0 wish }{\fs20\cf0 can bring a dead creature back to life by duplicating a }{\i\fs20\cf0 resurrection }{\fs20\cf0 spell. A }{\i\fs20\cf0 wish }{\fs20\cf0 
can revive a dead creature whose body has been destroyed, but the task takes two }{\i\fs20\cf0 wishes, }{\fs20\cf0 one to recreate the body and another to infuse the body with life again. A }{\i\fs20\cf0 wish }{\fs20\cf0 
cannot prevent a character who was brought back to life from losing an experience level.
\par }{\cf0 \bullet  }{\fs20\cf0 Transport travelers. A }{\i\fs20\cf0 wish }{\fs20\cf0 can lift one creature per caster level from anywhere 
on any plane and place those creatures anywhere else on any plane regardless of local conditions. An unwilling target gets a Will save to negate the effect, and spell resistance (if any) applies.
\par }{\cf0 \bullet  }{\fs20\cf0 Undo misfortune. A }{\i\fs20\cf0 wish }{\fs20\cf0 can undo a single recent event. The }{\i\fs20\cf0 wish }{\fs20\cf0 
forces a reroll of any roll made within the last round (including your last turn). Reality reshapes itself to accommodate the new result. For example, a }{\i\fs20\cf0 wish }{\fs20\cf0 could undo an opponent\rquote s successful save, a foe\rquote 
s successful critical hit (either the attack roll or the critical roll), a friend\rquote 
s failed save, and so on. The reroll, however, may be as bad as or worse than the original roll. An unwilling target gets a Will save to negate the effect, and spell resistance (if any) applies.
\par You may try to use a }{\i\fs20\cf0 wish }{\fs20\cf0 to produce greater effects than these, but doing so is dangerous. (The }{\i\fs20\cf0 wish }{\fs20\cf0 may pervert your intent into a literal but undesirable fulfillment or only a partial fulfillment.)

\par Duplicated spells allow saves and spell resistance as normal (but save DCs are for 9th-level spells).
\par }{\i\fs20\cf0 Material Component: }{\fs20\cf0 When a }{\i\fs20\cf0 wish }{\fs20\cf0 duplicates a spell with a material component that costs more than 10,000 gp, you must provide that component.
\par }{\i\fs20\cf0 XP Cost: }{\fs20\cf0 The minimum XP cost for casting }{\i\fs20\cf0 wish }{\fs20\cf0 is 5,000 XP. When a }{\i\fs20\cf0 wish }{\fs20\cf0 duplicates a spell that has an XP cost, you must pay 5,000 XP or that cost, whichever is more. When a }{
\i\fs20\cf0 wish }{\fs20\cf0 creates or improves a magic item, you must pay twice the normal XP cost for crafting or improving the item, plus an additional 5,000 XP.
